The paper proposes a method for learning rewards and policies from expert examples under unknown dynamics using generative adversarial networks. This involves inverse reinforcement learning, which is a subfield of machine learning that falls under the category of reinforcement learning. The paper also mentions the use of variational information maximization, which is a technique commonly used in deep learning and falls under the category of machine learning. The experiments involve high-dimensional complex control tasks, which are typically studied in the fields of robotics and control systems, falling under the categories of robotics (cs.RO) and systems and control (cs.SY). The paper also mentions testing the learned rewards in transfer learning problems, which can be related to computer vision (cs.CV) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
